WEBVTT

00:07.641 --> 00:08.542
‐ Previously on
"The Betty Broderick Story"...

00:09.076 --> 00:10.010
‐ What are you doing?

00:10.043 --> 00:12.446
‐ I never have time
to think about anything.

00:12.479 --> 00:15.482
If I could just
have some time by myself‐‐

00:15.516 --> 00:17.584
The kids are at camp
where you are not listed

00:17.618 --> 00:19.052
as next of kin.

00:19.086 --> 00:21.021
When they come back,
they'll be living with me.

00:21.054 --> 00:22.856
I'm seeking
an emergency judgment.

00:22.890 --> 00:24.258
I'm in love with her.

00:24.291 --> 00:26.727
‐ Was I ever imagining it?

00:26.760 --> 00:27.594
‐ No, you were right
the whole time.

00:27.628 --> 00:29.796
Will you marry me?
‐ Yes.

00:29.830 --> 00:30.931
[cheers and applause]

00:30.964 --> 00:32.299
‐ I'm divorced.

00:32.332 --> 00:34.268
I wasn't even there.
I didn't have a lawyer.

00:34.301 --> 00:37.437
‐ As is usual
in bifurcated divorces,

00:37.471 --> 00:39.106
we now move on
to court‐ordered mediation.

00:39.139 --> 00:42.042
‐ These contempt filings
serve to deliberately

00:42.075 --> 00:44.678
delay trial proceedings,
which will dilute

00:44.711 --> 00:45.946
Mrs. Broderick's share
of community property.

00:45.979 --> 00:47.014
‐ I have a calendar

00:47.047 --> 00:50.317
of backed up contempt motions
against your client.

00:50.350 --> 00:54.087
I'm imposing 19 day suspended,
6 days in jail.

00:57.157 --> 00:59.793
[tense music]

00:59.826 --> 01:02.663
[door buzzes]

01:04.364 --> 01:06.967
‐ Okay.
Here you go.

01:08.835 --> 01:11.972
Phone's against that wall.
Cab number's on the board.

01:12.005 --> 01:14.808
[change rattling]

01:14.841 --> 01:21.682
♪ ♪

01:33.260 --> 01:35.596
‐ Look, I got to go.
Bye.

01:35.629 --> 01:38.332
Mrs. Broderick?
Sid Montgomery,

01:38.365 --> 01:40.767
feature reporter
for the San Diego Register.

01:40.801 --> 01:44.204
‐ Oh, I'm‐‐I mean, I‐‐
‐ Your case, your divorce,

01:44.237 --> 01:45.939
might be the worst one
I've seen in this county.

01:45.973 --> 01:47.841
‐ [scoffs]

01:47.874 --> 01:49.343
You've seen a lot
of divorces, huh?

01:49.376 --> 01:53.547
‐ Well,
I cover the court, so yeah.

01:53.580 --> 01:56.183
So I know that
you've had it rough.

01:56.216 --> 01:58.051
I just got caught up
on all the proceedings

01:58.085 --> 01:59.720
and seen how long
they've been going on

01:59.753 --> 02:01.722
and that the date
for your property settlement

02:01.755 --> 02:04.191
hasn't been set yet, so,

02:04.224 --> 02:06.460
I thought maybe you might
have some things to say

02:06.493 --> 02:08.695
about all that on the record.

02:08.729 --> 02:11.064
Look, I get it.

02:11.098 --> 02:13.266
You want to get home, so...

02:13.300 --> 02:16.803
This is my desk phone
and my pager.

02:16.837 --> 02:18.071
Okay?

02:18.105 --> 02:19.873
Oh, and just remember,

02:19.906 --> 02:24.177
sometimes a problem
just needs a little daylight.

02:24.211 --> 02:27.214
[soft dramatic music]

02:27.247 --> 02:31.785
♪ ♪

02:31.818 --> 02:33.887
‐ I've seen the other side
of life now.

02:33.920 --> 02:37.624
♪ ♪

02:37.658 --> 02:41.461
The sordid, degrading side,
and I'm a part of it.

02:43.430 --> 02:45.165
And it actually
wasn't any worse

02:45.198 --> 02:46.733
than the hell in my head.

02:48.402 --> 02:51.171
He sent me to jail
and set me free.

02:51.204 --> 02:56.009
♪ ♪

02:56.043 --> 02:58.812
There's nothing more
liberating than to realize

02:58.845 --> 03:01.181
you don't have to live up
to anything anymore.

03:01.214 --> 03:08.388
♪ ♪

03:10.857 --> 03:14.461
‐ This just doesn't sound like
how you said she acts.

03:14.494 --> 03:16.630
Like, signing her name
to your legal documents‐‐

03:16.663 --> 03:18.965
‐ Yeah, and putting her voice
on his machine.

03:18.999 --> 03:21.268
‐ It's always at such a remove.

03:21.301 --> 03:23.637
Passive, you know?
‐ Plausible deniability.

03:23.670 --> 03:25.172
‐ Yeah, are we even sure
that's her handwriting?

03:25.205 --> 03:26.506
‐ I wondered that too.
It looks so‐‐

03:26.540 --> 03:28.408
‐ If it wasn't the whore,
who was it?

03:30.510 --> 03:31.645
‐ Uh‐‐

03:31.678 --> 03:33.980
‐ I'm sorry this happened to
you on top of everything else.

03:34.014 --> 03:36.183
It just‐‐
‐ Do you want to talk?

03:36.216 --> 03:38.018
‐ About what, the engagement?
We are talking about it.

03:38.051 --> 03:43.290
Also, how is Dan Broderick on
his knees in a bar newsworthy?

03:43.323 --> 03:46.526
‐ What about jail, Betty?
It must've been terrible.

03:46.560 --> 03:49.429
‐ Actually, it was interesting.
I made a lot of new friends.

03:52.165 --> 03:54.801
‐ Hey, did you ever
figure out an outfit

03:54.835 --> 03:56.103
for Tracy's graduation?

03:56.136 --> 03:57.270
Karen, did you find one
for Scott's?

03:57.304 --> 04:00.540
‐ Well, I thought I did, and it
looked great in the store,

04:00.574 --> 04:02.008
and it looked great
in my walk‐in,

04:02.042 --> 04:04.211
and then I go to answer
the phone wearing it,

04:04.244 --> 04:06.913
and I saw myself
in the hall mirror and died.

04:06.947 --> 04:08.815
‐ Never look at yourself
in the hall.

04:08.849 --> 04:10.484
[laughter]

04:10.517 --> 04:13.253
‐ Betty, what are you wearing?

04:13.286 --> 04:14.921
‐ I wonder if she thinks
she's coming.

04:14.955 --> 04:16.123
‐ Who?

04:16.156 --> 04:19.192
‐ Linda "The Whore" Kolkena,
to my daughter's graduation.

04:19.226 --> 04:22.696
Can't you just see her waltzing
her skinny ass right in there?

04:22.729 --> 04:26.967
All I can say is,
if that happens,

04:27.000 --> 04:31.638
then I'll know the bastard has
really lost his goddamn mind.

04:31.671 --> 04:32.806
[knocking]

04:37.210 --> 04:39.179
You were here before.

04:39.212 --> 04:46.319
♪ ♪

04:49.422 --> 04:50.757
[line trilling]

04:50.791 --> 04:53.293
‐ Feature desk.
This is Sid.

04:53.326 --> 04:54.561
‐ Hi, Sid.
It's Elisabeth Broderick.

04:54.594 --> 04:58.231
I was just given the date of
my property settlement hearing.

04:58.265 --> 05:00.867
‐ Well,
that's good news, right?

05:00.901 --> 05:02.736
‐ I don't know,

05:02.769 --> 05:04.905
but I decided I want
my side of the story out

05:04.938 --> 05:06.439
before it happens.

05:08.308 --> 05:15.448
♪ ♪

05:24.324 --> 05:27.761
with a 19 year old
and a red sports car.

05:27.794 --> 05:29.896
‐ Huh.
‐ The girlfriend, the Corvette,

05:29.930 --> 05:31.364
the "Risky Business"
sunglasses,

05:31.398 --> 05:34.034
a cover boy for
"Midlife Crisis Magazine."

05:34.067 --> 05:37.204
‐ [chuckles]
‐ "Cool, man, cool."

05:37.237 --> 05:40.273
I'd think it was hilarious
if it wasn't my husband.

05:40.307 --> 05:43.410
‐ Well, you have
a sense of humor about it.

05:43.443 --> 05:46.613
But so there might be
some people who could think

05:46.646 --> 05:48.481
your situation's
not all that bad.

05:48.515 --> 05:51.818
‐ Didn't I meet you in jail?
‐ Well, that's true.

05:51.852 --> 05:53.753
‐ I realize I'm lucky.

05:53.787 --> 05:56.256
I'm healthy.

05:56.289 --> 05:59.759
I have more than most people
will ever have in their life.

05:59.793 --> 06:01.862
But if Dan had defrauded
a business partner

06:01.895 --> 06:03.597
the way he did me
when he broke our contract,

06:03.630 --> 06:05.932
he'd be the one in jail,
not me.

06:08.134 --> 06:11.137
Our first baby graduating,

06:11.171 --> 06:12.739
our baby who was there
with us on our honeymoon

06:12.772 --> 06:14.841
and we didn't even know it.

06:17.210 --> 06:19.012
What will he say?

06:19.045 --> 06:22.415
He'll have to say something,
today of all days.

06:24.951 --> 06:26.786
He'll talk to me.
He'll be nice.

06:26.820 --> 06:28.455
He has to.

06:29.756 --> 06:30.991
[tense music]

06:31.024 --> 06:33.326
He'll be nice to me today.

06:33.360 --> 06:36.897
♪ ♪

06:36.930 --> 06:39.933
‐ Ladies and gentlemen,
our new graduates.

06:41.534 --> 06:43.370
‐ Hi.
‐ Hi, sweetie!

06:43.403 --> 06:48.975
♪ ♪

06:49.009 --> 06:51.311
‐ Oh, you're so pretty.

06:56.082 --> 06:57.150
‐ Mom.

06:57.183 --> 06:59.920
I couldn't find you.
Hi.

06:59.953 --> 07:02.222
[both laughing]

07:04.357 --> 07:07.193
‐ How could he bring her here?

07:07.227 --> 07:08.161
‐ I would‐‐

07:08.194 --> 07:11.331
‐ Did you try saying,
"This is a family event.

07:11.364 --> 07:14.401
"My mother is going
to see her daughter graduate,

07:14.434 --> 07:16.269
"and your presence
will just detract

07:16.303 --> 07:17.370
"from the joy at my achievement

07:17.404 --> 07:19.406
"because everyone
will just be talking about

07:19.439 --> 07:22.509
how my father left us
for the tacky office slut."

07:23.877 --> 07:26.379
‐ I‐‐
‐ Tell me I'm wrong.

07:26.413 --> 07:29.082
You can't.

07:29.115 --> 07:32.152
‐ Oh, my God, Trace.
Look at you.

07:32.185 --> 07:34.521
Are you just so proud, Betty?
‐ Hi, sweetie.

07:34.554 --> 07:39.359
‐ Remember from church the two
of them in the Noah's Ark play?

07:39.392 --> 07:41.594
Oh, Fred has that camera.
Let me take a picture.

07:41.628 --> 07:44.431
‐ Oh, yeah, sure.
‐ Please.

07:44.464 --> 07:46.066
Here we go.

07:46.099 --> 07:50.603
Okay, ready?
So beautiful.

07:50.637 --> 07:52.272
[camera shutter clicks]

07:52.305 --> 07:55.308
♪ ♪

07:55.342 --> 07:57.344
[sighs]

08:07.721 --> 08:09.089
[camera clicks]

08:10.790 --> 08:12.425
[shutter clicks]

08:12.459 --> 08:14.427
[indistinct chatter]

08:15.962 --> 08:18.865
[shutter clicking]
‐ Congratulations.

08:26.306 --> 08:29.242
[shutter clicking]

08:39.786 --> 08:43.256
‐ That Linda's outfit
was tacky, um,

08:43.289 --> 08:45.458
and that you were tacky
for bringing her,

08:45.492 --> 08:46.926
and a shithead.

08:46.960 --> 08:50.130
‐ In general,
or just for bringing her?

08:50.163 --> 08:53.133
And she never mentioned
anything about the engagement?

08:53.166 --> 08:54.634
Just the wedding china?

08:54.667 --> 08:56.970
‐ Yeah, she just wants it back.

08:57.003 --> 08:58.872
‐ Hmm.
‐ She talked about it a lot.

08:58.905 --> 09:02.275
Like, a lot.

09:02.308 --> 09:04.611
‐ And you're sure
that she didn't get it

09:04.644 --> 09:06.880
from the Coral Reef house?

09:06.913 --> 09:09.115
And she hasn't mentioned it
before, has she?

09:09.149 --> 09:11.351
‐ I've never seen it on any
of her lists of asks.

09:11.384 --> 09:14.320
‐ Hunter's coming.
I'm gonna change.

09:14.354 --> 09:16.990
‐ [sighs]

09:17.023 --> 09:19.159
I mean, if we could find it,
it could buy us some peace.

09:19.192 --> 09:21.394
‐ Why does she suddenly
want it now?

09:21.428 --> 09:23.930
‐ Oh, she just does.
Why anything?

09:25.598 --> 09:28.635
Linda, she probably didn't have
any film in the camera.

09:28.668 --> 09:29.736
‐ Of course she did.

09:29.769 --> 09:32.072
‐ Okay, but so
we're gonna go from that

09:32.105 --> 09:34.941
to getting an alarm system
for the house?

09:34.974 --> 09:37.143
She's gonna think she's
the master of mind control.

09:37.177 --> 09:38.711
How much do you think
she's gonna love it

09:38.745 --> 09:41.147
if we turn our house
into a fortress

09:41.181 --> 09:42.882
because she pretended
to take some photos of you?

09:42.916 --> 09:45.618
‐ It's not about
that specifically.

09:45.652 --> 09:46.553
It's not just about that.

09:46.586 --> 09:48.521
‐ Mm‐hmm.

09:48.555 --> 09:52.058
‐ Can't we get an alarm
just to have one?

09:52.092 --> 09:55.528
Do we have to care if Betty
might love it if we do?

09:55.562 --> 09:58.498
‐ No, but we have to care
about teaching her

09:58.531 --> 10:01.301
that she can get me to react.

10:01.334 --> 10:03.870
‐ When I filed a claim,
not only did they say

10:03.903 --> 10:05.805
they weren't gonna pay me
for one week,

10:05.839 --> 10:07.941
they docked me two years pay.

10:07.974 --> 10:10.944
So then I tried to file
a complaint,

10:10.977 --> 10:14.047
but HR said since I was
no longer an employee,

10:14.080 --> 10:17.250
I had no standing
to file anything.

10:17.283 --> 10:20.353
So then I just gave up.

10:20.386 --> 10:23.923
But with HALT, I finally
have people on my side.

10:23.957 --> 10:27.460
[applause]

10:27.494 --> 10:28.428
‐ Thank you, Margaret.

10:28.461 --> 10:31.397
‐ Thank you.

10:31.431 --> 10:34.234
‐ Okay, everyone, uh,
let's take a quick break.

10:36.803 --> 10:39.706
[indistinct chatter]

10:39.739 --> 10:42.909
Are you Elisabeth Broderick?

10:42.942 --> 10:44.077
I've heard about your case.

10:44.110 --> 10:44.944
‐ You don't know
the half of it.

10:44.978 --> 10:47.080
‐ Well, I know you don't
have a lawyer

10:47.113 --> 10:49.616
and that
your ex‐husband is one.

10:49.649 --> 10:52.986
And I know you have a lot
of kindred spirits in here.

10:53.019 --> 10:55.588
Would you be willing
to talk to the group?

10:58.658 --> 11:01.194
Yeah?
All right.

11:05.465 --> 11:07.467
Hey, everyone,
this is Elisabeth.

11:07.500 --> 11:09.135
She's gonna talk now.

11:12.338 --> 11:14.140
‐ Hi.

11:16.676 --> 11:20.813
I was married for 16 years,
and now I'm not.

11:20.847 --> 11:23.750
My husband hired a bimbo
and told me

11:23.783 --> 11:26.753
he didn't want me anymore,
after only a couple years

11:26.786 --> 11:29.656
of lying to me about it
every day first.

11:31.224 --> 11:33.626
He won't let me see my kids,
I don't have a settlement,

11:33.660 --> 11:35.261
and he fines me
when I call him a dickhead

11:35.295 --> 11:36.996
on his answering machine.

11:37.030 --> 11:39.165
[laughter]

11:39.199 --> 11:41.334
[soft dramatic music]

11:41.367 --> 11:43.403
But I'm sure things are gonna
start going my way

11:43.436 --> 11:45.672
now that he's president
of the San Diego Bar.

11:45.705 --> 11:48.408
[laughter]

11:51.010 --> 11:53.179
Also, call me "Betty."

11:58.484 --> 11:58.818
[seagulls chirping]

12:00.420 --> 12:02.388
‐ When's the interview
come out?

12:02.422 --> 12:04.090
‐ Soon‐‐
I hope before the hearing,

12:04.123 --> 12:07.160
so if Dan tries to get
the courtroom closed,

12:07.193 --> 12:09.095
people will know why.
‐ Hmm.

12:09.128 --> 12:10.830
What about an attorney?
Any luck?

12:10.863 --> 12:12.865
‐ You want to know
what I've decided?

12:12.899 --> 12:14.734
You ready?
‐ Mm‐hmm.

12:17.537 --> 12:19.572
‐ I'm gonna do it‐‐

12:19.606 --> 12:21.407
uh, appear, what's it, uh,

12:21.441 --> 12:23.343
pro se.

12:23.376 --> 12:25.011
Represent myself.

12:25.044 --> 12:26.012
Legalese.

12:26.045 --> 12:28.881
Why is "pro se" short
for "in propria persona?"

12:28.915 --> 12:30.883
Why isn't it "pro per?"

12:30.917 --> 12:33.419
Nobody knows better
what a cheat Dan is.

12:33.453 --> 12:34.787
Nobody knows
our history better.

12:34.821 --> 12:37.190
I will have him cornered
on the witness stand.

12:37.223 --> 12:39.259
He will have to go
on record in public

12:39.292 --> 12:42.128
and say that he put me
in an asylum, put me in jail,

12:42.161 --> 12:45.765
left me for the office whore,
let my son get lice,

12:45.798 --> 12:47.967
where he was
when our baby died.

12:50.003 --> 12:51.404
‐ Hmm.

12:54.007 --> 12:56.776
Do you have any sense
how much you owe Dan

12:56.809 --> 12:58.978
in terms of Epsteins?

12:59.012 --> 12:59.946
‐ Yeah, that is something

12:59.979 --> 13:01.781
I've been wondering
about‐‐Epsteins.

13:01.814 --> 13:03.383
Why do I have to reimburse Dan

13:03.416 --> 13:04.450
for the down payment
on my house,

13:04.484 --> 13:06.586
when he doesn't have to
repay me for the one on his?

13:06.619 --> 13:09.255
We were married
when we bought both houses.

13:09.289 --> 13:11.057
‐ Right.
Yeah.

13:11.090 --> 13:13.092
So this is where the date
of separation comes in.

13:13.126 --> 13:15.228
From the day he moved out,

13:15.261 --> 13:18.931
divorced or not,
it's all his money, not yours.

13:18.965 --> 13:20.466
See, this is why
an accountant would help,

13:20.500 --> 13:22.068
and a lawyer of course,

13:22.101 --> 13:24.737
to go after Dan's tax returns,
his partnerships,

13:24.771 --> 13:26.472
get a list of the cases
he worked on‐‐

13:26.506 --> 13:28.241
‐ Hilary asked for
all of that.

13:28.274 --> 13:30.410
Do I have it?
No.

13:30.443 --> 13:33.279
Besides, Dan's just gonna
doctor his books anyway.

13:33.313 --> 13:36.816
The only thing an attorney
ever did for me was lose.

13:36.849 --> 13:39.652
I can do that for free.

13:39.686 --> 13:41.220
‐ Well,

13:41.254 --> 13:44.257
will you at least let me
help you try not to lose?

13:44.290 --> 13:45.825
‐ Yes, I will.

13:45.858 --> 13:48.828
[tense music]

13:48.861 --> 13:54.334
♪ ♪

13:54.367 --> 13:55.835
[clears throat]

13:55.868 --> 13:58.971
Hi.
I'd like a copy of my file.

13:59.005 --> 14:01.341
‐ What's the caption?
‐ Of what?

14:01.374 --> 14:03.176
‐ Broderick versus Broderick.

14:05.645 --> 14:07.146
‐ [softly]
Wow, you know the lingo.

14:07.180 --> 14:08.348
‐ [softly] Well, in my divorce,

14:08.381 --> 14:09.649
the first hearing,

14:09.682 --> 14:12.518
the judge yelled at me
for not wearing a dress.

14:12.552 --> 14:13.753
He said in his courtroom,

14:13.786 --> 14:16.122
men needed to wear suits and
women needed to wear dresses.

14:16.155 --> 14:19.559
‐ What were you wearing?
‐ Liz Claiborne pants suit.

14:19.592 --> 14:21.494
‐ Nice.
Why are we whispering?

14:21.527 --> 14:23.963
‐ [chuckles]
I‐‐I don't know.

14:23.996 --> 14:25.498
[normal voice]
It's not the library.

14:25.531 --> 14:27.633
[both laughing]

14:27.667 --> 14:30.136
‐ File's not in the archive,
and it's not in the courtroom.

14:30.169 --> 14:32.004
I'll keep an eye out,
but I don't have it.

14:32.038 --> 14:33.172
Sorry.

14:33.206 --> 14:36.576
♪ ♪

14:36.609 --> 14:38.211
‐ I've never heard of this
happening,

14:38.244 --> 14:41.981
but we need
to rebuild that file.

14:42.014 --> 14:44.250
But do you have motions
Dan and his attorneys filed,

14:44.283 --> 14:45.852
any summonses?

14:45.885 --> 14:48.154
‐ I have all his letters.

14:48.187 --> 14:50.523
I have everything
he ever wrote me.

14:52.024 --> 14:55.161
‐ Calendar number one,
Broderick versus Broderick.

14:55.194 --> 14:56.396
The plaintiff,
Daniel Broderick,

14:56.429 --> 14:59.665
is present with his attorney
Walter Mills.

14:59.699 --> 15:02.001
Also present is the defendant,

15:02.034 --> 15:04.003
Elisabeth Broderick,

15:04.036 --> 15:07.540
who is appearing pro se.

15:07.573 --> 15:10.076
‐ Your Honor, I understand
the press are present today.

15:10.109 --> 15:12.044
My client has always been
deeply concerned

15:12.078 --> 15:13.246
of the negative impact

15:13.279 --> 15:15.715
that civil review
can have on his children,

15:15.748 --> 15:17.183
and so we would request

15:17.216 --> 15:20.052
that the courtroom
be closed to the public.

15:21.554 --> 15:22.989
‐ Mrs. Broderick?

15:27.093 --> 15:30.897
‐ I'm for opening it up
to everyone on principle.

15:30.930 --> 15:33.699
It's a public proceeding.

15:33.733 --> 15:35.868
I have nothing to hide.

15:35.902 --> 15:38.104
And if I'm such the awful,

15:38.137 --> 15:41.774
guilty person
Dan paints me to be,

15:41.808 --> 15:45.044
why is he so afraid
of people knowing it?

15:45.077 --> 15:46.646
‐ Well, as an adult,

15:46.679 --> 15:49.916
Mr. Broderick can live
with the choices he's made.

15:49.949 --> 15:53.686
The issue here involves
your vulnerable children.

15:53.719 --> 15:55.455
‐ I don't think
it's only about

15:55.488 --> 15:56.956
hurting or not hurting
my children.

15:56.989 --> 15:58.591
‐ It's a terrible dilemma.

15:58.624 --> 16:01.461
If you demand
an open proceeding,

16:01.494 --> 16:02.962
there is the inference that

16:02.995 --> 16:06.532
that is not an appropriate
parenting decision,

16:06.566 --> 16:09.035
which could adversely
affect your position

16:09.068 --> 16:12.004
in the custody matter.

16:12.038 --> 16:14.974
Whereas if you choose to have
the proceeding closed,

16:15.007 --> 16:18.044
you may be sacrificing
your own personal needs

16:18.077 --> 16:20.012
as you believe them to be.

16:20.046 --> 16:24.350
♪ ♪

16:24.383 --> 16:26.552
‐ Yes, okay.

16:28.020 --> 16:30.790
Close it, please.

16:30.823 --> 16:31.891
Close it.

16:34.293 --> 16:35.628
‐ All right,
ladies and gentlemen,

16:35.661 --> 16:37.096
please clear the court.

16:37.129 --> 16:39.832
[soft indistinct chatter]

16:55.014 --> 16:55.882
‐ Besides custody
of the minor marital children,

16:56.916 --> 16:58.451
Your Honor will face a problem
of major proportions

16:58.484 --> 16:59.685
when attempting to determine
a settlement of property

16:59.719 --> 17:03.222
in this case.

17:03.256 --> 17:05.658
In addition, the issue
of spousal support promises

17:05.691 --> 17:08.928
to entail significant argument,
but I'm confident

17:08.961 --> 17:11.364
that with testimony
and evidence submitted,

17:11.397 --> 17:13.366
Your Honor will find in favor
of Mr. Broderick.

17:13.399 --> 17:15.401
Thank you.

17:15.434 --> 17:17.470
‐ Mrs. Broderick,

17:17.503 --> 17:19.672
would you like to make
your opening statement now

17:19.705 --> 17:22.041
or wait until
you begin your case?

17:22.074 --> 17:24.577
‐ Isn't‐‐isn't this
the beginning?

17:29.549 --> 17:32.718
I don't have one prepared.

17:32.752 --> 17:34.954
I can make one.

17:38.758 --> 17:41.227
I'm happy to be here

17:41.260 --> 17:45.565
to get some resolution
in this case,

17:45.598 --> 17:49.201
get back some semblance
of normalcy

17:49.235 --> 17:51.871
in a life that feels like
it's been under siege

17:51.904 --> 17:53.639
for years.

17:53.673 --> 17:57.743
My support, I would just like
to be able to go on living.

17:57.777 --> 18:00.046
I would like what's fair,
what takes into account

18:00.079 --> 18:03.115
in some way my contribution.

18:06.252 --> 18:10.056
So I hope that we can
settle something.

18:10.089 --> 18:12.224
Thank you.

18:12.258 --> 18:15.261
‐ Yes, I do have many
investment properties,

18:15.294 --> 18:17.430
especially in Colorado,
but with the collapse

18:17.463 --> 18:20.600
of oil values earlier
in this decade and Colorado

18:20.633 --> 18:23.102
being an energy state,
their value shrunk.

18:23.135 --> 18:25.037
I don't like it,
I'm sure Bets doesn't like it,

18:25.071 --> 18:26.172
but that's it.

18:26.205 --> 18:29.842
All of my wealth really
is in my law practice,

18:29.875 --> 18:35.047
which, uh, I've had evaluated,
and if the court agrees,

18:35.081 --> 18:38.351
I intend to offer Bets
half that value.

18:39.685 --> 18:43.723
‐ Would you say that
once you achieved success,

18:43.756 --> 18:45.992
Mrs. Broderick was happy?

18:46.025 --> 18:49.061
‐ The more money I made,
the more she spent.

18:49.095 --> 18:51.130
But no,
she was never satisfied.

18:51.163 --> 18:53.265
If it was expensive,
she needed it.

18:53.299 --> 18:55.234
‐ How would you describe
the support that

18:55.267 --> 18:56.435
Mrs. Broderick
provided you

18:56.469 --> 18:57.703
when you began
your legal career?

18:57.737 --> 18:59.505
‐ Nonexistent.
‐ How would describe

18:59.538 --> 19:02.942
Mrs. Broderick's
itemized expenses

19:02.975 --> 19:06.145
that she's using as the basis
for her support allocation?

19:06.178 --> 19:08.447
‐ Outrageous.
‐ Would you characterize

19:08.481 --> 19:12.251
Mrs. Broderick
as driven by greed?

19:12.284 --> 19:14.220
‐ Yes, and frankly,

19:14.253 --> 19:16.822
I'm gonna have to tighten
my expenses very soon‐‐

19:16.856 --> 19:19.425
not just with a daughter
going to college,

19:19.458 --> 19:21.794
but I am getting remarried,

19:21.827 --> 19:23.996
starting a new family.

19:24.030 --> 19:26.165
I anticipate there
will be expenses

19:26.198 --> 19:28.467
in connection with that.

19:28.501 --> 19:31.103
‐ Mr. Montgomery,
it's Elisabeth Broderick again.

19:31.137 --> 19:34.940
I was just calling
about the article again,

19:34.974 --> 19:37.109
when it's coming out?

19:37.143 --> 19:39.812
It should've happened by now,
don't you think?

19:39.845 --> 19:42.982
Please let me know.
Thanks.

19:43.015 --> 19:45.184
[door closes]

19:45.217 --> 19:46.852
Come here.

19:46.886 --> 19:53.025
♪ ♪

19:53.059 --> 19:54.827
Where were you?

19:54.860 --> 19:56.562
‐ The movies.
Remember?

19:56.595 --> 19:59.999
‐ I remember
it started at 6:25.

20:00.032 --> 20:01.534
‐ What are you doing?

20:01.567 --> 20:05.438
‐ Preparing
to examine a witness.

20:05.471 --> 20:07.873
‐ You are?
What witness?

20:07.907 --> 20:11.143
Dad?
[scoffs]

20:11.177 --> 20:13.813
Shit.

20:13.846 --> 20:15.848
Wow.

20:15.881 --> 20:19.051
Okay.

20:19.085 --> 20:21.020
‐ What movie did you see again?

20:21.053 --> 20:22.722
‐ "Scrooged."

20:22.755 --> 20:24.390
‐ Oh, yeah?

20:24.423 --> 20:25.624
Come over here
where I can see you.

20:25.658 --> 20:27.193
‐ Why, what's your deal?
‐ Do it.

20:27.226 --> 20:28.794
Or you're grounded.

20:35.568 --> 20:37.369
Now you're grounded
for whatever it was

20:37.403 --> 20:39.405
you were really doing.

20:39.438 --> 20:42.274
[pencil scribbling]

20:45.111 --> 20:47.246
[soft dramatic music]

20:47.279 --> 20:51.283
‐ You know,
when you examine Dad,

20:51.317 --> 20:53.152
you should ask about
all the nicknames

20:53.185 --> 20:55.087
he and Linda call you.

20:55.121 --> 20:58.657
"Crazy," obviously,

20:58.691 --> 21:03.095
and "the monster,"

21:03.129 --> 21:06.532
and "the beast."

21:06.565 --> 21:08.367
‐ Your Honor, I don't have
any firsthand knowledge

21:08.400 --> 21:11.237
of the numbers presented by
Mr. Broderick and Mr. Mills.

21:11.270 --> 21:14.573
Nor do I know the law
or really the rules of trial.

21:14.607 --> 21:17.109
But I'll do my best
to play the game,

21:17.143 --> 21:20.179
and if you'll just let me know

21:20.212 --> 21:22.214
if I'm making any mistakes
along the way.

21:22.248 --> 21:29.355
♪ ♪

21:32.224 --> 21:35.528
‐ Mr. Broderick,

21:35.561 --> 21:37.696
when did this case start?

21:37.730 --> 21:39.799
‐ February 28th, 1985.

21:39.832 --> 21:42.601
‐ Oh, is that when
you think it was?

21:42.635 --> 21:44.770
‐ At our separation,
is that what you mean?

21:44.804 --> 21:46.639
‐ It isn't.

21:46.672 --> 21:49.875
When was the moment
this divorce really started?

21:51.477 --> 21:54.380
‐ April 12th, 1969.

21:55.748 --> 21:58.450
‐ And what's the relevance
of that date for the record?

22:00.085 --> 22:03.789
‐ That was the date
we got married, Your Honor.

22:10.663 --> 22:11.664
‐ What I'm trying to get at
by asking "When did it start,"

22:13.532 --> 22:15.367
is when did I first
become aware

22:15.401 --> 22:16.869
of your affair
with Linda Kolkena?

22:16.902 --> 22:18.604
‐ Objection.
Relevance.

22:18.637 --> 22:20.606
‐ Sustained.

22:20.639 --> 22:23.008
In California, Mrs. Broderick,

22:23.042 --> 22:27.046
as I'm sure you're aware,
we recognize no‐fault divorce.

22:27.079 --> 22:29.181
Therefore the issue here today

22:29.215 --> 22:32.251
is not one of whose fault
the divorce was.

22:32.284 --> 22:33.619
We are only here

22:33.652 --> 22:36.956
to decide the question
of division of property,

22:36.989 --> 22:39.091
the assets of the community,

22:39.124 --> 22:41.427
and to determine
the appropriate parent

22:41.460 --> 22:42.628
for the custody
of the minor children.

22:42.661 --> 22:46.198
‐ I was manipulated purposely
and with malice

22:46.232 --> 22:50.102
before this case was even filed
by an expert attorney.

22:50.135 --> 22:52.404
I'm trying to show how‐‐

22:52.438 --> 22:55.741
how Dan cut me off
from our community assets

22:55.774 --> 22:59.545
from the start of his affair
with Linda Kolkena.

22:59.578 --> 23:04.049
‐ Then see if there isn't
anything to develop

23:04.083 --> 23:05.584
that relates to the assets.

23:05.618 --> 23:08.320
You must refer to the assets,

23:08.354 --> 23:11.657
not to any alleged affair,
okay?

23:11.690 --> 23:14.526
‐ Okay.
Thank you, Your Honor.

23:18.130 --> 23:20.332
Remember what my reaction was
when you hired this girl?

23:20.366 --> 23:21.667
‐ Objection.
Relevance.

23:21.700 --> 23:23.335
‐ Sustained.

23:23.369 --> 23:25.938
You're still in
the area of fault.

23:27.406 --> 23:29.942
‐ Do you remember me
telling you,

23:29.975 --> 23:32.478
"Fire your assistant
or get out of this house?"

23:32.511 --> 23:33.746
‐ Objection.
‐ Sustained.

23:33.779 --> 23:35.247
‐ Wait‐‐

23:35.281 --> 23:37.716
‐ Stay away from
the alleged affair.

23:37.750 --> 23:41.120
I cannot be more clear, okay?

23:41.153 --> 23:43.355
‐ You want me to just
change the whole subject?

23:43.389 --> 23:45.591
Will that make you happy?
‐ Yes, ma'am.

23:49.128 --> 23:52.498
‐ Do you remember how we lived
when we first got married?

23:52.531 --> 23:54.633
‐ In New York?
‐ Yeah.

23:54.667 --> 23:57.670
How we lived mostly
on my salary,

23:57.703 --> 23:59.838
how we went through my savings?

23:59.872 --> 24:02.141
‐ I remember you had
a small nest egg

24:02.174 --> 24:04.677
from babysitting,
I think it was.

24:04.710 --> 24:07.379
‐ You remember how hard it was?

24:07.413 --> 24:10.382
All the jobs I had,
even after I was pregnant?

24:10.416 --> 24:13.852
‐ I remember you had
various odd jobs, Tupperware,

24:13.886 --> 24:16.789
the one from the department
store on the holidays,

24:16.822 --> 24:19.024
but I don't recall them
being particularly helpful.

24:19.058 --> 24:21.660
‐ You're saying
we weren't poor?

24:21.694 --> 24:23.395
Did we ever have
to go on food stamps?

24:23.429 --> 24:24.363
‐ I don't know.

24:24.396 --> 24:26.398
We got food stamps
once or twice.

24:26.432 --> 24:30.135
‐ You remember we didn't have
a crib when Tracy was born?

24:30.169 --> 24:31.170
‐ What?
No, I don't.

24:31.203 --> 24:34.573
‐ You don't remember
we didn't have a crib?

24:34.606 --> 24:38.711
‐ From my memory,
in my mind, uh,

24:38.744 --> 24:41.313
these were‐‐
it was a busy time.

24:41.347 --> 24:45.784
We were stretched but we
always came through all right.

24:55.527 --> 24:57.997
‐ Oh, yeah.

24:58.030 --> 24:59.865
Did I support you financially

24:59.898 --> 25:01.767
while you were
in medical school?

25:01.800 --> 25:04.336
‐ You contributed to the upkeep
of the household, yes.

25:04.370 --> 25:05.671
‐ Why would I do that?

25:05.704 --> 25:07.706
‐ I assume it was an investment

25:07.740 --> 25:11.744
in your future as the wife
of a wealthy doctor.

25:11.777 --> 25:13.712
‐ You're saying
I only did it for myself?

25:15.714 --> 25:17.883
Is that what you thought
at the time?

25:19.318 --> 25:20.953
‐ I was busy at the time.

25:20.986 --> 25:23.622
‐ If I was so invested in being
a wealthy doctor's wife,

25:23.655 --> 25:24.723
how'd you convince me to agree

25:24.757 --> 25:26.725
to the idea of you
going to law school?

25:26.759 --> 25:29.762
‐ Well, I told you that

25:29.795 --> 25:33.599
I could make more money
as a lawyer with an MD.

25:33.632 --> 25:36.035
‐ Did you contribute
to our household income

25:36.068 --> 25:37.536
while you were in law school?

25:37.569 --> 25:39.505
No, you did not.
Did I?

25:39.538 --> 25:43.208
‐ We took out loans.
‐ For tuition.

25:43.242 --> 25:45.244
‐ But yes,

25:45.277 --> 25:49.181
you did get some money
in between pregnancies.

25:51.717 --> 25:54.353
‐ When did you first start
telling our children

25:54.386 --> 25:56.155
that I was mentally ill?

25:56.188 --> 25:57.756
‐ I don't recall
putting it that way.

25:57.790 --> 25:59.558
‐ When I would confront you
with questions

25:59.591 --> 26:02.628
about a certain party,

26:02.661 --> 26:04.763
wasn't your answer
that I was crazy?

26:04.797 --> 26:07.733
‐ Could you be more specific?

26:07.766 --> 26:09.735
‐ Were you seen
out and around town

26:09.768 --> 26:12.371
with Linda Kolkena in 1983?

26:12.404 --> 26:13.672
‐ Objection.

26:13.705 --> 26:14.940
‐ Mrs. Broderick,
you've been warned.

26:14.973 --> 26:17.009
‐ Okay, but this isn't
an issue of fault.

26:17.042 --> 26:19.478
His only grounds for keeping
the kids is his claim

26:19.511 --> 26:21.647
that I need psychiatric help.

26:21.680 --> 26:24.817
He submitted reports to you,
audio tapes

26:24.850 --> 26:26.618
claiming I'm a mental case,
that I'm crazy.

26:26.652 --> 26:28.153
I'm just trying to prove
that I'm not.

26:28.187 --> 26:30.522
I'm trying to establish

26:30.556 --> 26:33.025
why I might've been angry
at the time that‐‐

26:33.058 --> 26:37.996
‐ Mr. Broderick's outside
activities are not assistive

26:38.030 --> 26:40.999
to your present ability
to parent.

26:41.033 --> 26:42.734
Sustained.

26:46.238 --> 26:49.041
‐ An Epstein credit ensures
one spouse will be reimbursed

26:49.074 --> 26:53.512
by the other for expenses
or debts after separation.

26:53.545 --> 26:55.180
‐ Haven't you dragged
out payments

26:55.214 --> 26:56.215
and encumbered properties

26:56.248 --> 26:58.117
in order to increase
my Epsteins to you?

26:58.150 --> 26:59.618
‐ No, I have not.
‐ Why else wouldn't you

26:59.651 --> 27:03.889
have paid off the lake house
or the Colorado properties?

27:03.922 --> 27:07.559
Why haven't you paid back
your Harvard Law School loans?

27:07.593 --> 27:10.162
Why did you charge me
half of these payments

27:10.195 --> 27:12.731
two years after you left me?

27:12.764 --> 27:15.934
‐ I pay my bills automatically
every month.

27:15.968 --> 27:20.539
I've been paying for Harvard
on a monthly basis since 1974.

27:20.572 --> 27:24.143
I just kept doing it,
uh, out of habit.

27:24.176 --> 27:27.813
If you're insinuating
that this is some kind of plot,

27:27.846 --> 27:30.015
I didn't learn about
Epstein credits

27:30.048 --> 27:32.718
until long after
our separation.

27:32.751 --> 27:34.553
‐ Wasn't your first lawyer
Doug Layton,

27:34.586 --> 27:36.522
an expert on Epsteins?

27:36.555 --> 27:39.591
‐ Mrs. Broderick,
you misunderstand the point.

27:39.625 --> 27:40.792
‐ I don't think I do.

27:40.826 --> 27:44.930
‐ Mr. Broderick either paid
your expenses or he didn't,

27:44.963 --> 27:48.834
and you're looking for
skeletons where there are none.

27:48.867 --> 27:51.003
‐ Dan, as I was looking through
boxes of papers,

27:51.036 --> 27:54.506
I happened on
two bank withdrawals you made,

27:54.540 --> 27:57.876
one for $175,000
closing out an account,

27:57.910 --> 28:01.713
and one for $80,000
emptying another one,

28:01.747 --> 28:05.384
both in February 1985.

28:05.417 --> 28:08.620
Both before you left me.

28:08.654 --> 28:10.656
On those days,
you withdrew that money

28:10.689 --> 28:14.760
February 5th and February 22nd.

28:14.793 --> 28:18.931
Did you know you'd be
leaving me on February 28th?

28:18.964 --> 28:20.899
‐ No.

28:20.933 --> 28:25.604
‐ But yet you closed out
two accounts that I know of.

28:25.637 --> 28:28.307
How did that money affect the
valuation of your law practice?

28:28.340 --> 28:30.809
'Cause it wasn't included
in the appraisal.

28:30.842 --> 28:33.212
[tense music]

28:33.245 --> 28:35.280
‐ It should have.

28:35.314 --> 28:39.051
Uh, those figures
should have been adjusted.

28:39.084 --> 28:42.254
Upward.

28:42.287 --> 28:45.757
‐ Your Honor, uh,
at which point in time

28:45.791 --> 28:48.627
will you be valuing
Dan's law practice?

28:48.660 --> 28:51.263
At the time of separation
four years ago,

28:51.296 --> 28:53.165
or at the current time?

28:53.198 --> 28:56.902
‐ Well, the community asset
can be valued either/or.

28:56.969 --> 28:59.304
‐ But you get to decide which.

28:59.338 --> 29:01.240
‐ That is true.

29:01.273 --> 29:02.474
‐ When?

29:02.507 --> 29:05.777
‐ When the case is ended,
uh, based on the facts

29:05.811 --> 29:07.746
and the circumstances
presented.

29:07.779 --> 29:09.514
‐ Hmm.
Okay.

29:09.548 --> 29:11.183
The appraiser hired
by Mr. Broderick

29:11.216 --> 29:15.520
valued the practice
on February 28th, 1985.

29:15.554 --> 29:17.256
I didn't find anything
in the record

29:17.289 --> 29:22.461
evaluating its current worth,
so you only have the "either."

29:22.494 --> 29:24.596
You don't actually
have the "or."

29:24.630 --> 29:27.633
‐ That is true.

29:27.666 --> 29:30.502
‐ Is that
my responsibility to get?

29:30.535 --> 29:33.338
‐ Correct.

29:33.372 --> 29:37.976
‐ So do I need an expert,
or do I just ask Mr. Broderick?

29:38.010 --> 29:40.679
‐ Well, you can ask
Mr. Broderick

29:40.712 --> 29:43.048
the question you want to ask,

29:43.081 --> 29:46.118
and to the extent
he knows the answer,

29:46.151 --> 29:48.387
we'll hear what he has to say.

29:48.420 --> 29:53.058
♪ ♪

29:53.091 --> 29:56.194
‐ Can you explain why
the value of your practice‐‐

29:56.228 --> 29:58.864
the cases, the hardware,
the computers, the cars,

29:58.897 --> 30:02.567
the pension, everything,
comes out to less in value

30:02.601 --> 30:05.404
than what you earn
in a single year?

30:05.437 --> 30:08.573
‐ Objection.
‐ Sustained.

30:08.607 --> 30:10.642
Argumentative.

30:10.676 --> 30:13.879
‐ Jeez.
Really?

30:16.615 --> 30:18.884
The night you left our house,
what did you say to me?

30:18.917 --> 30:22.587
‐ What did I‐‐
‐ February 28, 1985,

30:22.621 --> 30:23.922
you said you were leaving
because

30:23.955 --> 30:27.826
you needed time to think
about your life.

30:27.859 --> 30:28.960
‐ I said‐‐
‐ What about your life,

30:28.994 --> 30:32.397
you couldn't say,
but is it not true that that‐‐

30:32.431 --> 30:33.899
‐ I said I am leaving you,

30:33.932 --> 30:36.034
that we can't live
together anymore,

30:36.068 --> 30:39.204
that it's been too bad
for too long between us.

30:39.237 --> 30:42.107
It doesn't work.
I have to go.

30:43.308 --> 30:45.243
‐ At any point
did you use the word

30:45.277 --> 30:48.380
"separation" or "divorce?"
‐ No.

30:48.413 --> 30:52.117
Because I hadn't decided
to do that yet.

30:52.150 --> 30:55.287
[soft dramatic music]

30:55.320 --> 30:57.089
♪ ♪

30:57.122 --> 31:00.525
I don't know when
I first concluded

31:00.559 --> 31:02.527
that you have
emotional problems,

31:02.561 --> 31:04.930
but it was a long time ago.

31:06.832 --> 31:09.568
I understand your anger.
I understand your hatred.

31:09.601 --> 31:11.236
‐ Yeah, you understand,

31:11.269 --> 31:15.006
yet you drag me through
the legal system for years.

31:15.040 --> 31:18.243
‐ And now here we are.

31:18.276 --> 31:20.445
After everything
I've given you,

31:20.479 --> 31:22.114
after everything you have,

31:22.147 --> 31:24.950
I don't think you have a
legitimate basis for complaint.

31:24.983 --> 31:27.386
